  keywords     = {heterochromatin, phase separation, HP1a, liquid-liquid demixing, 3D genome, nucleation},
  note         = {Demonstrates that HP1a protein undergoes liquid-liquid phase separation in vitro and nucleates into foci with liquid properties during early heterochromatin domain formation in Drosophila embryos. Heterochromatin domains exhibit phase-separation dynamics: sensitivity to hydrophobic disruption, reduced probe diffusion, and inert probe exclusion at domain boundaries. Provides biophysical evidence for a nucleation threshold in heterochromatin assembly---domains form via phase separation and mature into structure with liquid and stable compartments. Supports the sigmoidal (not linear) functional form for B_strength = f(ProB methylation)---below a critical HP1 density, liquid domain nucleation fails. Certainty: 0.75 (Nature, two-lab independent, Drosophila + mammalian cell validation).},
